07849nam a22007935i 9780822387480DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223874807 a10.1515/97808223874802doi  a(DE-B1597)553021  a(OCoLC)609245014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a306/.09822200aCultural Agency in the Americas /ced. by Doris Sommer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b19 b&w photos, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Wiggle Room -- t1. Media -- tIntervening from and through Research Practice: Meditations on the Cuzco Workshop -- tBetween Technology and Culture: Communication and Modernity in Latin America -- tDNA of Performance -- tA City that Improvises Its Globalization -- t2. Maneuvers -- tThe Cultural Agency of Wounded Bodies Politic: Ethnicity and Gender as Prosthetic Support in Postwar Guatemala -- tTradition, Transnationalism, and Gender in the Afro-Brazilian Candomblé -- tThe Discourses of Diversity: Language, Ethnicity, and Interculturality in Latin America -- tConspiracy on the Sidelines: How the Maya Won the War -- tRadio Taino and the Cuban Quest for Identi . . . qué? -- tOlodum’s Transcultural Spaces: Community and Difference in Afro- Brazilian Contemporary Performance -- tPolitical Construction and Cultural Instrumentalities of Indigenism in Brazil, with Echoes from Latin America -- tQuestioning State Geographies of Inclusion in Argentina: The Cultural Politics of Organizations with Mapuche Leadership and Philosophy -- t3. Cautions -- tCultural Agency and Political Struggle in the Era of the Indio Permitido -- tThe Crossroads of Faith: Heroism and Melancholia in the Colombian ‘‘Violentologists’’ (1980–2000) -- tAfterword: A Fax, Two Moles, a Consul, and a Judge -- tAfterword: Spread It Around! -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Cultural agency” refers to a range of creative activities that contribute to society, including pedagogy, research, activism, and the arts. Focusing on the connections between creativity and social change in the Americas, this collection encourages scholars to become cultural agents by reflecting on exemplary cases and thereby making them available as inspirations for more constructive theory and more innovative practice. Creativity supports democracy because artistic, administrative, and interpretive experiments need margins of freedom that defy monolithic or authoritarian regimes. The ingenious ways in which people pry open dead-ends of even apparently intractable structures suggest that cultural studies as we know it has too often gotten stuck in critique. Intellectual responsibility can get beyond denunciation by acknowledging and nurturing the resourcefulness of common and uncommon agents.Based in North and South America, scholars from fields including anthropology, performance studies, history, literature, and communications studies explore specific variations of cultural agency across Latin America. Contributors reflect, for example, on the paradoxical programming and reception of a state-controlled Cuban radio station that connects listeners at home and abroad; on the intricacies of indigenous protests in Brazil; and the formulation of cultural policies in cosmopolitan Mexico City. One contributor notes that trauma theory targets individual victims when it should address collective memory as it is worked through in performance and ritual; another examines how Mapuche leaders in Argentina perceived the pitfalls of ethnic essentialism and developed new ways to intervene in local government. Whether suggesting modes of cultural agency, tracking exemplary instances of it, or cautioning against potential missteps, the essays in this book encourage attentiveness to, and the multiplication of, the many extraordinary instantiations of cultural resourcefulness and creativity throughout Latin America and beyond.Contributors. Arturo Arias, Claudia Briones, Néstor García Canclini, Denise Corte, Juan Carlos Godenzzi, Charles R. Hale, Ariana Hernández-Reguant, Claudio Lomnitz, Jesús Martín Barbero, J. Lorand Matory, Rosamel Millamán, Diane M. Nelson, Mary Louise Pratt, Alcida Rita Ramos, Doris Sommer, Diana Taylor, Santiago Villaveces  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt and statezLatin America. 0aArts and societyzLatin America. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aSocial changezLatin America. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aArias, Arturo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbero, Jesus Martin.1 aBarbero, Jesús Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriones, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanclini, Néstor Garcia.1 aCorte, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodenzzi, Juan Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHale, Charles R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández-Reguant, Ariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLomnitz, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatory, J. Lorand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillamán, Rosamel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Diane M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c